# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: janet-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C was initially developed as a successor to the B programming language at Bell Labs by Ritchie between 1972 and 1973.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Its initial purpose was to construct utilities running on Unix, and was later applied to re-implementing the kernel of the Unix operating system.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] During the 1980s, C gradually gained popularity, leading to it becoming one of the most widely used programming languages, with C compilers available for practically all modern computer architectures and operating systems.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The book *The C Programming Language*, co-authored by the original language designer, served for many years as the *de facto* standard for the language.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C has been standardized since 1989 by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and, subsequently, jointly by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C is an imperative procedural language, supporting structured programming, lexical variable scope, and recursion, with a static type system.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It was designed to be compiled to provide low-level access to memory and language constructs that map efficiently to machine instructions, all with minimal runtime support.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Despite its low-level capabilities, the language was designed to encourage cross-platform programming.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A standards-compliant C program written with portability in mind can be compiled for a wide variety of computer platforms and operating systems with few changes to its source code.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Although neither C nor its standard library provide some popular features found in other languages, it is flexible enough to support them.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For example, object orientation and garbage collection are provided by external libraries GLib Object System and Boehm garbage collector, respectively.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since 2000, C has typically ranked as the most or second-most popular language in the TIOBE index.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C is an imperative, procedural language with a free-form source layout.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Statements are terminated by semicolons and grouped into blocks using curly braces.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] All executable code is contained in functions rather than top-level statements.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The language has a relatively small number of keywords, and user-defined identifiers are not distinguished from keywords by any sigil.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Parameters are passed by value; pass-by-reference is achieved with pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A function's return value may be ignored, and while a function cannot normally be nested inside another function, some translators support this.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C supports recursion, and run-time polymorphism may be achieved using function pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Control flow is provided through constructs such as `if`, `for`, `do`, `while`, and `switch`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The language offers arithmetic; bitwise; and logical operators including `+`, `+=`, `++`, `&`, `||`, and multiple assignments may be performed in a single statement.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A variable declared inside a block is accessible only within that block and only below its declaration.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Data typing is weakly enforced and static, with implicit conversion between primitive types.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] User-defined types allow aliasing of type specifiers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Arrays are defined and accessed with square-bracket notation, for example `month[11]`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] User-defined structure types let related data elements be passed and copied as a unit, though two structures cannot be compared without custom code to compare each field.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Unions support overlapping members, allowing multiple data types to share the same memory location, and enumeration types support aliasing integer values.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C lacks a dedicated string type but provides syntax for null-terminated strings, with associated handling in its standard library.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The language supports low-level access to computer memory via pointers, procedure-like constructs in the form of functions returning `void`, and dynamic memory allocation through standard library functions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It includes the C preprocessor for macro definition, source-file inclusion, and conditional compilation.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Modularity is supported by processing files separately, with visibility controlled through the `static` and `extern` attributes.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Functionality is minimized in the core language, with relatively complex features such as I/O, string manipulation, and mathematical functions being provided through standard libraries.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The resulting compiled code has relatively straightforward requirements of the underlying platform, making C desirable for operating and embedded systems.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The "Hello, World!" program example that appeared in the first edition of *K&R* has become the model for an introductory program in most programming textbooks.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The program prints "hello, world" to the standard output.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The first line is a preprocessor directive, indicated by `#include`, which causes the preprocessor to replace that line of code with the text of the `stdio.h` header file, which contains declarations for input and output functions including `printf`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The angle brackets around `stdio.h` indicate that the header file can be located using a search strategy that selects header files provided with the compiler over files with the same name that may be found in project-specific directories.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The next code line declares the entry point function `main`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The run-time environment calls this function to begin program execution.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The type specifier `int` indicates that the function returns an integer value.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The `void` parameter list indicates that the function consumes no arguments.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The run-time environment actually passes two arguments (typed `int` and `char *[]`), but this implementation ignores them.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The ISO C standard (section 5.1.2.2.1) requires syntax that either is void or these two arguments – a special treatment not afforded to other functions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The opening curly brace indicates the beginning of the code that defines the function.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The next line of code calls (diverts execution to) the C standard library function `printf` with the address of the first character of a null-terminated string specified as a string literal.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The text `\n` is an escape sequence that denotes the newline character which when output in a terminal results in moving the cursor to the beginning of the next line.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Even though `printf` returns an `int` value, it is silently discarded.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The semicolon `;` terminates the call statement.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The closing curly brace indicates the end of the `main` function.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Prior to C99, an explicit `return 0;` statement was required at the end of `main` function, but since C99, the `main` function (as being the initial function call) implicitly returns `0` upon reaching its final closing curly brace.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The origin of C is closely tied to the development of the Unix operating system, originally implemented in assembly language on a PDP-7 by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson, incorporating several ideas from colleagues.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Eventually, they decided to port the operating system to a PDP-11.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The original PDP-11 version of Unix was also developed in assembly language.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Thompson wanted a programming language for developing utilities for the new platform.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] He first tried writing a Fortran compiler, but he soon gave up the idea and instead created a cut-down version of the recently developed systems programming language called BCPL.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The official description of BCPL was not available at the time, and Thompson modified the syntax to be less 'wordy' and similar to a simplified ALGOL known as SMALGOL.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] He called the result *B*, describing it as "BCPL semantics with a lot of SMALGOL syntax".
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Like BCPL, B had a bootstrapping compiler to facilitate porting to new machines.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Ultimately, few utilities were written in B because it was too slow and could not take advantage of PDP-11 features such as byte addressability.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Unlike BCPL's `// comment` marking comments up to the end of the line, B adopted `/* comment */` as the comment delimiter, more akin to PL/1, and allowing comments to appear in the middle of lines.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 1971, Ritchie started to improve B, to use the features of the more-powerful PDP-11.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A significant addition was a character data type.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Thompson started to use NB to write the Unix kernel, and his requirements shaped the direction of the language development.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Through to 1972, richer types were added to the NB language.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] NB had arrays of `int` and `char`, and to these types were added pointers, the ability to generate pointers to other types, arrays of all types, and types to be returned from functions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Arrays within expressions were effectively treated as pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A new compiler was written, and the language was renamed C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C compiler and some utilities made with it were included in Version 2 Unix, which is also known as Research Unix.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] At Version 4 Unix, released in November 1973, the Unix kernel was extensively re-implemented in C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] By this time, the C language had acquired some powerful features such as `struct` types.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The preprocessor was introduced around 1973 at the urging of Alan Snyder and also in recognition of the usefulness of the file-inclusion mechanisms available in BCPL and PL/I.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Its original version provided only included files and simple string replacements: `#include` and `#define` of parameterless macros.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Soon after that, it was extended, mostly by Mike Lesk and then by John Reiser, to incorporate macros with arguments and conditional compilation.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Unix was one of the first operating system kernels implemented in a language other than assembly.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Earlier instances include the Multics system (which was written in PL/I) and Master Control Program (MCP) for the Burroughs B5000 (which was written in ALGOL) in 1961.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In and around 1977, Ritchie and Stephen C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Johnson made further changes to the language to facilitate portability of the Unix operating system.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Johnson's Portable C Compiler served as the basis for several implementations of C on new platforms.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 1978, Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie published the first edition of *The C Programming Language*.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Known as *K&R* from the initials of its authors, the book served for many years as an informal specification of the language.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The version of C that it describes is commonly referred to as "**K&R C**".
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] As this was released in 1978, it is now also referred to as *C78*.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The second edition of the book covers the later ANSI C standard, described below.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Although later versions of C require functions to have an explicit type declaration, K&R C only requires functions that return a type other than `int` to be declared before use.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Functions used without prior declaration were presumed to return `int`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The declaration of `long_function()` (on line 1) is required since it returns `long`; not `int`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Function `int_function` can be called (line 11) even though it is not declared since it returns `int`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Also, variable `intvar` does not need to be declared as type `int` since that is the default type for `register` keyword.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since function declarations did not include information about arguments, type checks were not performed, although some compilers would issue a warning if different calls to a function used different numbers or types of arguments.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Tools such as Unix's lint utility were developed that (among other things) checked for consistency of function use across multiple source files.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In the years following the publication of K&R C, several features were added to the language, supported by compilers from AT&T (in particular PCC) and other vendors.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The popularity of the language, lack of agreement on standard library interfaces, and lack of compliance to the K&R specification, led to standardization efforts.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] During the late 1970s and 1980s, versions of C were implemented for a wide variety of mainframe computers, minicomputers, and microcomputers, including the IBM PC, as its popularity increased significantly.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 1983 the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) formed a committee, X3J11, to establish a standard specification of C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] X3J11 based the C standard on the Unix implementation; however, the non-portable portion of the Unix C library was handed off to the IEEE working group 1003 to become the basis for the 1988 POSIX standard.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 1989, the C standard was ratified as ANSI X3.159-1989 "Programming Language C".
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] This version of the language is often referred to as ANSI C, Standard C, or sometimes **C89**.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 1990 the ANSI C standard (with formatting changes) was adopted by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) as ISO/IEC 9899:1990, which is sometimes called **C90**.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Therefore, the terms "C89" and "C90" refer to the same programming language.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] ANSI, like other national standards bodies, no longer develops the C standard independently, but defers to the international C standard, maintained by the working group ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG14.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] National adoption of an update to the international standard typically occurs within a year of ISO publication.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] One of the aims of the C standardization process was to produce a superset of K&R C, incorporating many of the subsequently introduced unofficial features.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The standards committee also included several additional features such as function prototypes (borrowed from C++), `void` pointers, support for international character sets and locales, and preprocessor enhancements.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Although the syntax for parameter declarations was augmented to include the style used in C++, the K&R interface continued to be permitted, for compatibility with existing source code.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C89 is supported by current C compilers, and most modern C code is based on it.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Any program written only in Standard C and without any hardware-dependent assumptions will run correctly on any platform with a conforming C implementation, within its resource limits.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In cases where code must be compilable by either standard-conforming or K&R C-based compilers, the `__STDC__` macro can be used to split the code into Standard and K&R sections to prevent the use on a K&R C-based compiler of features available only in Standard C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] After the ANSI/ISO standardization process, the C language specification remained relatively static for several years.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 1995, Normative Amendment 1 to the 1990 C standard (ISO/IEC 9899/AMD1:1995, known informally as C95) was published, to correct some details and to add more extensive support for international character sets.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C standard was further revised in the late 1990s, leading to the publication of ISO/IEC 9899:1999 in 1999, which is commonly referred to as "C99".
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It has since been amended three times by Technical Corrigenda.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Many of these had already been implemented as extensions in several C compilers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C99 is for the most part backward compatible with C90, but is stricter in some ways; in particular, a declaration that lacks a type specifier no longer has `int` implicitly assumed.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined with value `199901L` to indicate that C99 support is available.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] GCC, Solaris Studio, and other C compilers now support many or all of the new features of C99.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C compiler in Microsoft Visual C++, however, implements the C89 standard and those parts of C99 that are required for compatibility with C++11.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In addition, the C99 standard requires support for identifiers using Unicode in the form of escaped characters (e.g.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] `\u0040` or `\U0001f431`) and suggests support for raw Unicode names.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Work began in 2007 on another revision of the C standard, informally called "C1X" until its official publication of ISO/IEC 9899:2011 on December 8, 2011.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C standards committee adopted guidelines to limit the adoption of new features that had not been tested by existing implementations.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C11 standard adds numerous new features to C and the library, including type generic macros, anonymous structures, improved Unicode support, atomic operations, multi-threading, and bounds-checked functions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It also makes some portions of the existing C99 library optional, and improves compatibility with C++.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined as `201112L` to indicate that C11 support is available.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C17 is an informal name for ISO/IEC 9899:2018, a standard for the C programming language published in June 2018.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It introduces no new language features, only technical corrections, and clarifications to defects in C11.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined as `201710L` to indicate that C17 support is available.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C23 is an informal name for the current major C language standard revision.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It was known as "C2X" through most of its development.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It builds on past releases, introducing features like new keywords, additional meaning for `auto` to provide type inference when declaring variables, new types including `nullptr_t` and `_BitInt(N)`, and expansions to the standard library.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined as `202311L` to indicate that C23 support is available.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C2Y is an informal name for the next major C language standard revision, after C23 (C2X), that is hoped to be released later in the 2020s, hence the '2' in "C2Y".
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] An early working draft of C2Y was released in February 2024 as N3220 by the working group ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG14.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Historically, embedded C programming requires non-standard extensions to the C language to support exotic features such as fixed-point arithmetic, multiple distinct memory banks, and basic I/O operations.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In 2008, the C Standards Committee published a technical report extending the C language to address these issues by providing a common standard for all implementations to adhere to.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] It includes a number of features not available in normal C, such as fixed-point arithmetic, named address spaces, and basic I/O hardware addressing.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C has a formal grammar specified by the C standard.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Line endings are generally not significant in C; however, line boundaries do have significance during the preprocessing phase.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Comments may appear either between the delimiters `/*` and `*/`, or (since C99) following `//` until the end of the line.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Comments delimited by `/*` and `*/` do not nest, and these sequences of characters are not interpreted as comment delimiters if they appear inside string or character literals.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C source files contain declarations and function definitions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Function definitions, in turn, contain declarations and statements.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Declarations either define new types using keywords such as `struct`, `union`, and `enum`, or assign types to and perhaps reserve storage for new variables, usually by writing the type followed by the variable name.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Keywords such as `char` and `int` specify built-in types.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Sections of code are enclosed in braces (`{` and `}`, sometimes called "curly brackets") to limit the scope of declarations and to act as a single statement for control structures.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] As an imperative language, C uses *statements* to specify actions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The most common statement is an *expression statement*, consisting of an expression to be evaluated, followed by a semicolon; as a side effect of the evaluation, functions may be called and variables assigned new values.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] To modify the normal sequential execution of statements, C provides several control-flow statements identified by reserved keywords.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Structured programming is supported by `if` ... [`else`] conditional execution and by `do` ...
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] `while`, `while`, and `for` iterative execution (looping).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The `for` statement has separate initialization, testing, and reinitialization expressions, any or all of which can be omitted.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] `break` and `continue` can be used within the loop.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Break is used to leave the innermost enclosing loop statement and continue is used to skip to its reinitialisation.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] There is also a non-structured `goto` statement, which branches directly to the designated label within the function.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] `switch` selects a `case` to be executed based on the value of an integer expression.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Different from many other languages, control-flow will fall through to the next `case` unless terminated by a `break`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Expressions can use a variety of built-in operators and may contain function calls.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The order in which arguments to functions and operands to most operators are evaluated is unspecified.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The evaluations may even be interleaved.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] However, all side effects (including storage to variables) will occur before the next "sequence point"; sequence points include the end of each expression statement, and the entry to and return from each function call.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Sequence points also occur during evaluation of expressions containing certain operators (`&&`, `||`, `?:` and the comma operator).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] This permits a high degree of object code optimization by the compiler, but requires C programmers to take more care to obtain reliable results than is needed for other programming languages.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Kernighan and Ritchie say in the Introduction of *The C Programming Language*: "C, like any other language, has its blemishes.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Some of the operators have the wrong precedence; some parts of the syntax could be better." The C standard did not attempt to correct many of these blemishes, because of the impact of such changes on already existing software.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The *newline* character indicates the end of a text line; it need not correspond to an actual single character, although for convenience C treats it as such.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The POSIX standard mandates a portable character set which adds a few characters (notably "@") to the basic C source character set.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Both standards do not prescribe any particular value encoding—ASCII and EBCDIC both comply with these standards, since they include at least those basic characters, even though they use different encoded values for those characters.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Additional multi-byte encoded characters may be used in string literals, but they are not entirely portable.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since C99 multi-national Unicode characters can be embedded portably within C source text by using `\uXXXX` or `\UXXXXXXXX` encoding (where `X` denotes a hexadecimal character).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The basic C execution character set contains the same characters, along with representations for the null character, alert, backspace, and carriage return.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Run-time support for extended character sets has increased with each revision of the C standard.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] All versions of C have reserved words that are case sensitive.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] As reserved words, they cannot be used for variable names.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Most of the recently reserved words begin with an underscore followed by a capital letter, because identifiers of that form were previously reserved by the C standard for use only by implementations.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since existing program source code should not have been using these identifiers, it would not be affected when C implementations started supporting these extensions to the programming language.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Some standard headers do define more convenient synonyms for underscored identifiers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Some of those words were added as keywords with their conventional spelling in C23 and the corresponding macros were removed.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Prior to C89, `entry` was reserved as a keyword.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C supports a rich set of operators, which are symbols used within an expression to specify the manipulations to be performed while evaluating that expression.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C uses the operator `=` (used in mathematics to express equality) to indicate assignment, following the precedent of Fortran and PL/I, but unlike ALGOL and its derivatives.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C uses the operator `==` to test for equality.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The similarity between the operators for assignment and equality may result in the accidental use of one in place of the other, and in many cases the mistake does not produce an error message (although some compilers produce warnings).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For example, the conditional expression `if (a == b + 1)` might mistakenly be written as `if (a = b + 1)`, which will be evaluated as `true` unless the value of `a` is `0` after the assignment.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C operator precedence is not always intuitive.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For example, the operator `==` binds more tightly than (is executed prior to) the operators `&` (bitwise AND) and `|` (bitwise OR) in expressions such as `x & 1 == 0`, which must be written as `(x & 1) == 0` if that is the coder's intent.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The type system in C is static and weakly typed, which makes it similar to the type system of ALGOL descendants such as Pascal.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] There are built-in types for integers of various sizes, both signed and unsigned, floating-point numbers, and enumerated types (`enum`).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Integer type `char` is often used for single-byte characters.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] There are also derived types including arrays, pointers, records (`struct`), and unions (`union`).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C is often used in low-level systems programming where escapes from the type system may be necessary.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Some find C's declaration syntax unintuitive, particularly for function pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C's *usual arithmetic conversions* allow for efficient code to be generated, but can sometimes produce unexpected results.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For example, a comparison of signed and unsigned integers of equal width requires a conversion of the signed value to unsigned.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] This can generate unexpected results if the signed value is negative.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C supports the use of pointers, a type of reference that records the address or location of an object or function in memory.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers can be *dereferenced* to access data stored at the address pointed to, or to invoke a pointed-to function.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers can be manipulated using assignment or pointer arithmetic.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The run-time representation of a pointer value is typically a raw memory address (perhaps augmented by an offset-within-word field), but since a pointer's type includes the type of the thing pointed to, expressions including pointers can be type-checked at compile time.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Pointer arithmetic is automatically scaled by the size of the pointed-to data type.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers are used for many purposes in C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Text strings are commonly manipulated using pointers into arrays of characters.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Dynamic memory allocation is performed using pointers; the result of a `malloc` is usually cast to the data type of the data to be stored.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Many data types, such as trees, are commonly implemented as dynamically allocated `struct` objects linked together using pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers to other pointers are often used in multi-dimensional arrays and arrays of `struct` objects.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers to functions (*function pointers*) are useful for passing functions as arguments to higher-order functions (such as qsort or bsearch), in dispatch tables, or as callbacks to event handlers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A *null pointer value* explicitly points to no valid location.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Dereferencing a null pointer value is undefined, often resulting in a segmentation fault.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Null pointer values are useful for indicating special cases such as no "next" pointer in the final node of a linked list, or as an error indication from functions returning pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In appropriate contexts in source code, such as for assigning to a pointer variable, a *null pointer constant* can be written as `0`, with or without explicit casting to a pointer type, as the `NULL` macro defined by several standard headers or, since C23 with the constant `nullptr`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In conditional contexts, null pointer values evaluate to `false`, while all other pointer values evaluate to `true`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Void pointers (`void *`) point to objects of unspecified type, and can therefore be used as "generic" data pointers.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since the size and type of the pointed-to object is not known, void pointers cannot be dereferenced, nor is pointer arithmetic on them allowed, although they can easily be (and in many contexts implicitly are) converted to and from any other object pointer type.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Careless use of pointers is potentially dangerous.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Because they are typically unchecked, a pointer variable can be made to point to any arbitrary location, which can cause undesirable effects.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In general, C is permissive in allowing manipulation of and conversion between pointer types, although compilers typically provide options for various levels of checking.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Some other programming languages address these problems by using more restrictive reference types.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Array types in C are traditionally of a fixed, static size specified at compile time.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The more recent C99 standard also allows a form of variable-length arrays.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] However, it is also possible to allocate a block of memory (of arbitrary size) at run time, using the standard library's `malloc` function, and treat it as an array.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since arrays are always accessed (in effect) via pointers, array accesses are typically not checked against the underlying array size, although some compilers may provide bounds checking as an option.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Array bounds violations are therefore possible and can lead to various repercussions, including illegal memory accesses, corruption of data, buffer overflows, and run-time exceptions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] C does not have a special provision for declaring multi-dimensional arrays, but rather relies on recursion within the type system to declare arrays of arrays, which effectively accomplishes the same thing.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The index values of the resulting "multi-dimensional array" can be thought of as increasing in row-major order.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Multi-dimensional arrays are commonly used in numerical algorithms (mainly from applied linear algebra) to store matrices.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The structure of the C array is well suited to this particular task.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] However, in early versions of C the bounds of the array must be known fixed values or else explicitly passed to any subroutine that requires them, and dynamically sized arrays of arrays cannot be accessed using double indexing.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] (A workaround for this was to allocate the array with an additional "row vector" of pointers to the columns.) C99 introduced "variable-length arrays" which address this issue.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The subscript notation `x[i]` (where `x` designates a pointer) is syntactic sugar for `*(x+i)`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Taking advantage of the compiler's knowledge of the pointer type, the address that `x + i` points to is not the base address (pointed to by `x`) incremented by `i` bytes, but rather is defined to be the base address incremented by `i` multiplied by the size of an element that `x` points to.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Thus, `x[i]` designates the `i+1`th element of the array.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Furthermore, in most expression contexts (a notable exception is as operand of `sizeof`), an expression of array type is automatically converted to a pointer to the array's first element.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] This implies that an array is never copied as a whole when named as an argument to a function, but rather only the address of its first element is passed.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Therefore, although function calls in C use pass-by-value semantics, arrays are in effect passed by reference.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The total size of an array `x` can be determined by applying `sizeof` to an expression of array type.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The size of an element can be determined by applying the operator `sizeof` to any dereferenced element of an array `A`, as in `n = sizeof A[0]`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Thus, the number of elements in a declared array `A` can be determined as `sizeof A / sizeof A[0]`.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Note, that if only a pointer to the first element is available as it is often the case in C code because of the automatic conversion described above, the information about the full type of the array and its length are lost.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] One of the most important functions of a programming language is to provide facilities for managing memory and the objects that are stored in memory.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] These three approaches are appropriate in different situations and have various trade-offs.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For example, static memory allocation has little allocation overhead, automatic allocation may involve slightly more overhead, and dynamic memory allocation can potentially have a great deal of overhead for both allocation and deallocation.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Most C programs make extensive use of all three.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Where possible, automatic or static allocation is usually simplest because the storage is managed by the compiler, freeing the programmer of the potentially error-prone chore of manually allocating and releasing storage.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] However, many data structures can change in size at run time, and since static allocations (and automatic allocations before C99) must have a fixed size at compile time, there are many situations in which dynamic allocation is necessary.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Prior to the C99 standard, variable-sized arrays were a common example of this.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Unless otherwise specified, static objects contain zero or null pointer values upon program startup.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Automatically and dynamically allocated objects are initialized only if an initial value is explicitly specified; otherwise they initially have indeterminate values (typically, whatever bit pattern happens to be present in the storage, which might not even represent a valid value for that type).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] If the program attempts to access an uninitialized value, the results are undefined.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Many modern compilers try to detect and warn about this problem, but both false positives and false negatives can occur.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Heap memory allocation has to be synchronized with its actual usage in any program to be reused as much as possible.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For example, if the only pointer to a heap memory allocation goes out of scope or has its value overwritten before it is deallocated explicitly, then that memory cannot be recovered for later reuse and is essentially lost to the program, a phenomenon known as a *memory leak*.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Conversely, it is possible for memory to be freed but referenced subsequently, leading to unpredictable results.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Typically, the failure symptoms appear in a portion of the program unrelated to the code that causes the error, making it difficult to diagnose the failure.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Such issues are ameliorated in languages with automatic garbage collection.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The C programming language uses libraries as its primary method of extension.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In C, a library is a set of functions contained within a single "archive" file.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Each library typically has a header file, which contains the prototypes of the functions contained within the library that may be used by a program, and declarations of special data types and macro symbols used with these functions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] For a program to use a library, it must include the library's header file, and the library must be linked with the program, which in many cases requires compiler flags (e.g., `-lm`, shorthand for "link the math library").
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The most common C library is the C standard library, which is specified by the ISO and ANSI C standards and comes with every C implementation (implementations which target limited environments such as embedded systems may provide only a subset of the standard library).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] This library supports stream input and output, memory allocation, mathematics, character strings, and time values.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Several separate standard headers (for example, `stdio.h`) specify the interfaces for these and other standard library facilities.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Another common set of C library functions are those used by applications specifically targeted for Unix and Unix-like systems, especially functions which provide an interface to the kernel.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] These functions are detailed in various standards such as POSIX and the Single UNIX Specification.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Since many programs have been written in C, there are a wide variety of other libraries available.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Libraries are often written in C because C compilers generate efficient object code; programmers then create interfaces to the library so that the routines can be used from higher-level languages like Java, Perl, and Python.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] File input and output (I/O) is not part of the C language itself but instead is handled by libraries (such as the C standard library) and their associated header files (e.g.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] File handling is generally implemented through high-level I/O which works through streams.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A stream is from this perspective a data flow that is independent of devices, while a file is a concrete device.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] The high-level I/O is done through the association of a stream to a file.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] In the C standard library, a buffer (a memory area or queue) is temporarily used to store data before it is sent to the final destination.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] This reduces the time spent waiting for slower devices, for example a hard drive or solid-state drive.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Low-level I/O functions are not part of the standard C library but are generally part of "bare metal" programming (programming that is independent of any operating system such as most embedded programming).
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] With few exceptions, implementations include low-level I/O.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A number of tools have been developed to help C programmers find and fix statements with undefined behavior or possibly erroneous expressions, with greater rigor than that provided by the compiler.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Automated source code checking and auditing tools exist, such as Lint.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] A common practice is to use Lint to detect questionable code when a program is first written.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Once a program passes Lint, it is then compiled using the C compiler.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Also, many compilers can optionally warn about syntactically valid constructs that are likely to actually be errors.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] MISRA C is a proprietary set of guidelines to avoid such questionable code, developed for embedded systems.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] There are also compilers, libraries, and operating system level mechanisms for performing actions that are not a standard part of C, such as bounds checking for arrays, detection of buffer overflow, serialization, dynamic memory tracking, and automatic garbage collection.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p01] Memory management checking tools like Purify or Valgrind and linking with libraries containing special versions of the memory allocation functions can help uncover run-time errors in memory usage.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C has been widely used to implement end-user and system-level applications.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C is widely used for systems programming in implementing operating systems and embedded system applications.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Computer games are often built from a combination of languages.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C has featured significantly, especially for those games attempting to obtain best performance from computer platforms.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Historically, C was sometimes used for web development using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) as a "gateway" for information between the web application, the server, and the browser.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C may have been chosen over interpreted languages because of its speed, stability, and near-universal availability.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] It is no longer common practice for web development to be done in C, and many other web development languages are popular.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Applications where C-based web development continues include the HTTP configuration pages on routers, IoT devices and similar, although even here some projects have parts in higher-level languages e.g. the use of Lua within OpenWRT.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Two popular web servers, Apache HTTP Server and Nginx, are written in C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C's close-to-the-metal approach allows for the construction of these high-performance software systems.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C is sometimes used as an intermediate language by implementations of other languages.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] This approach may be used for portability or convenience; by using C as an intermediate language, additional machine-specific code generators are not necessary.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C has some features, such as line-number preprocessor directives and optional superfluous commas at the end of initializer lists, that support compilation of generated code.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] However, some of C's shortcomings have prompted the development of other C-based languages specifically designed for use as intermediate languages, such as C--.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Also, contemporary major compilers GCC and LLVM both feature an intermediate representation that is not C, and those compilers support front ends for many languages including C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C enables programmers to create efficient implementations of algorithms and data structures, because the layer of abstraction from hardware is thin, and its overhead is low, an important criterion for computationally intensive programs.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] For example, the GNU Multiple Precision Arithmetic Library, the GNU Scientific Library, Mathematica, and MATLAB are completely or partially written in C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Many languages support calling library functions in C; for example, the Python-based framework NumPy uses C for the high-performance and hardware-interacting aspects.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] A consequence of C's wide availability and efficiency is that compilers, libraries and interpreters of other programming languages are often implemented in C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] For example, the reference implementations of Python, Perl, Ruby, and PHP are written in C.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] For some purposes, restricted styles of C have been adopted, e.g.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] MISRA C or CERT C, in an attempt to reduce the opportunity for unwanted behaviour.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Databases such as CWE attempt to count the ways that systems in general, especially those coded in C, have potential vulnerabilities, along with recommendations for mitigation.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] There are tools that can mitigate some of the drawbacks.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Contemporary C compilers include checks which may generate warnings to help identify many potential bugs.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C's use of pointers can be made less risky by use of instruction set architecture extensions such as *CHERI* or *Permission Overlay Extensions*.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] These techniques change the fundamental nature of pointers at a hardware level to include bounds checks and purposes, which can help prevent buffer over-runs and inappropriate heap accesses.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Since the early 2020s the Linux kernel has sections written in Rust, a language which has specific measures to improve safety.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Many languages developed after C were influenced by and borrowed aspects of C, including C++, C#, C shell, D, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Limbo, LPC, Objective-C, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, Rust, Swift, Verilog and SystemVerilog.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Some claim that the most pervasive influence has been syntactical – that these languages combine the statement and expression syntax of C with type systems, data models and large-scale program structures that differ from those of C, sometimes radically.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Several C or near-C interpreters exist, including Ch and CINT, which can also be used for scripting.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] When object-oriented programming languages became popular, C++ and Objective-C were two different extensions of C that provided object-oriented capabilities.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Both languages were originally implemented as source-to-source compilers; source code was translated into C, and then compiled with a C compiler.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] The C++ programming language (originally named "C with Classes") was devised by Bjarne Stroustrup as an approach to providing object-oriented functionality with a C-like syntax.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] C++ adds greater typing strength, scoping, and other tools useful in object-oriented programming, and permits generic programming via templates.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Nearly a superset of C, C++ now supports most of C, with a few exceptions.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Objective-C was originally a thin layer on top of C, and remains a strict superset of C that permits object-oriented programming using a hybrid dynamic/static typing paradigm.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] Objective-C derives its syntax from both C and Smalltalk: syntax that involves preprocessing, expressions, function declarations, and function calls is inherited from C, while the syntax for object-oriented features was originally taken from Smalltalk.
[src:janet-language/c-programming-language-p02] In addition to C++ and Objective-C, Ch, Cilk, and Unified Parallel C are nearly supersets of C.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:janet-language/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:janet-language/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:janet-language/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] In computer science, a **fiber** is a particularly lightweight thread of execution.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Like threads, fibers share address space.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] However, fibers use cooperative multitasking while threads use preemptive multitasking.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Threads often depend on the kernel's thread scheduler to preempt a busy thread and resume another thread; fibers yield themselves to run another fiber while executing.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] The key difference between fibers and kernel threads is that fibers use cooperative context switching, instead of preemptive time-slicing.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Fibers (sometimes called stackful coroutines or user mode cooperatively scheduled threads) and stackless coroutines (compiler synthesized state machines) represent two distinct programming facilities with vast performance and functionality differences.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Because fibers multitask cooperatively, thread safety is less of an issue than with preemptively scheduled threads, and synchronization constructs including spinlocks and atomic operations are unnecessary when writing fibered code, as they are implicitly synchronized.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] However, many libraries yield a fiber implicitly as a method of conducting non-blocking I/O; as such, some caution and documentation reading is advised.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] A disadvantage is that fibers cannot utilize multiprocessor machines without also using preemptive threads; however, an M:N threading model with no more preemptive threads than CPU cores can be more efficient than either pure fibers or pure preemptive threading.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] In some server programs, fibers are used to soft block themselves to allow their single-threaded parent programs to continue working.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] In this design, fibers are used mostly for I/O access which does not need CPU processing.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] This allows the main program to continue with what it is doing.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Fibers yield control to the single-threaded main program, and when the I/O operation is completed fibers continue where they left off.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Less support from the operating system is needed for fibers than for threads.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] They can be implemented in modern Unix systems using the library functions getcontext, setcontext and swapcontext in `<ucontext.h>`, as in GNU Portable Threads, or in assembler as `boost::fibers`.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] On Microsoft Windows, fibers are created using the `ConvertThreadToFiber` and `CreateFiber` calls; a fiber that is currently suspended may be resumed in any thread.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Fiber-local storage, analogous to thread-local storage, may be used to create unique copies of variables.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Symbian OS used a similar concept to fibers in its Active Scheduler.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] An active object contained one fiber to be executed by the Active Scheduler when one of several outstanding asynchronous calls completed.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Several Active objects could be waiting to execute (based on priority) and each one had to restrict its own execution time.
[src:janet-language/fiber-computer-science] Fibers can be implemented without operating system support, although some operating systems or libraries provide explicit support for them.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp does not support re-entrant continuations, but does support several ways of handling escape continuations.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Often, the same algorithm can be expressed in Lisp in either an imperative or a functional style.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] As noted above, Scheme tends to favor the functional style, using tail recursion and continuations to express control flow.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] However, imperative style is still quite possible.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] The style preferred by many Common Lisp programmers may seem more familiar to programmers used to structured languages such as C, while that preferred by Schemers more closely resembles pure-functional languages such as Haskell.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Because of Lisp's early heritage in list processing, it has a wide array of higher-order functions relating to iteration over sequences.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] In many cases where an explicit loop would be needed in other languages (like a `for` loop in C) in Lisp the same task can be accomplished with a higher-order function.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] A good example is a function which in Scheme is called `map` and in Common Lisp is called `mapcar`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] This applies the `+` function to each corresponding pair of list elements, yielding the result `(11 22 33 44 55)`.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Lisp syntax lends itself naturally to recursion.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Mathematical problems such as the enumeration of recursively defined sets are simple to express in this notation.
[src:janet-language/lisp-programming-language] Genera, renamed Open Genera, by Symbolics; Medley, written in Interlisp, originally a family of graphical operating systems that ran on Xerox's later Star workstations; Mezzano; Interim; ChrysaLisp, by developers of Tao Systems' TAOS; and also the Guix System for GNU/Linux.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In computer programming, a **macro** (short for "**macro instruction**"; from Greek μακρο*-* 'long, large') is a rule or pattern that specifies how a certain input should be mapped to a replacement output.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Applying a macro to an input is known as **macro expansion**.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The input and output may be a sequence of lexical tokens or characters, or a syntax tree.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Character macros are supported in software applications to make it easy to invoke common command sequences.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Token and tree macros are supported in some programming languages to enable code reuse or to extend the language, sometimes for domain-specific languages.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros are used to make a sequence of computing instructions available to the programmer as a single program statement, making the programming task less tedious and less error-prone.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Thus, they are called "macros" because a "big" block of code can be expanded from a "small" sequence of characters.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros often allow positional or keyword parameters that dictate what the conditional assembler program generates and have been used to create entire programs or program suites according to such variables as operating system, platform or other factors.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The term derives from "macro instruction", and such expansions were originally used in generating assembly language code.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] During the 1980s, macro programs – originally SmartKey, then SuperKey, KeyWorks, Prokey – were very popular, first as a means to automatically format screenplays, then for a variety of user-input tasks.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] These programs were based on the terminate-and-stay-resident mode of operation and applied to all keyboard input, no matter in which context it occurred.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] They have to some extent fallen into obsolescence following the advent of mouse-driven user interfaces and the availability of keyboard and mouse macros in applications, such as word processors and spreadsheets, making it possible to create application-sensitive keyboard macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Keyboard macros can be used in massively multiplayer online role-playing games (MMORPGs) to perform repetitive, but lucrative tasks, thus accumulating resources.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] As this is done without human effort, it can skew the economy of the game.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] For this reason, use of macros is a violation of the TOS or EULA of most MMORPGs, and their administrators spend considerable effort to suppress them.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Keyboard and mouse macros that are created using an application's built-in macro features are sometimes called **application macros**.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] They are created by carrying out the sequence once and letting the application record the actions.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] An underlying macro programming language, most commonly a scripting language, with direct access to the features of the application may also exist.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The programmers' text editor Emacs (short for "editing macros") follows this idea to a conclusion.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In effect, most of the editor is made of macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Emacs was originally devised as a set of macros in the editing language TECO; it was later ported to dialects of Lisp.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Another programmers' text editor, Vim (a descendant of vi), also has an implementation of keyboard macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] It can record into a register (macro) what a person types on the keyboard and it can be replayed or edited just like VBA macros for Microsoft Office.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Vim also has a scripting language called Vimscript to create macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) is a programming language included in Microsoft Office from Office 97 through Office 2019 (although it was available in some components of Office prior to Office 97).
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] However, its function has evolved from and replaced the macro languages that were originally included in some of these applications.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] XEDIT, running on the Conversational Monitor System (CMS) component of VM, supports macros written in EXEC, EXEC2 and REXX, and some CMS commands were actually wrappers around XEDIT macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The Hessling Editor (THE), a partial clone of XEDIT, supports Rexx macros using Regina and Open Object REXX (oorexx).
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Many common applications, and some on PCs, use Rexx as a scripting language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] VBA has access to most Microsoft Windows system calls and executes when documents are opened.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This makes it relatively easy to write computer viruses in VBA, commonly known as macro viruses.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In the mid-to-late 1990s, this became one of the most common types of computer virus.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] However, during the late 1990s and to date, Microsoft has been patching and updating its programs.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In addition, current anti-virus programs immediately counteract such attacks.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] A **parameterized macro** is a macro that is able to insert given objects into its expansion.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This gives the macro some of the power of a function.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This causes `PI` to always be replaced with `3.14159` wherever it occurs.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] What this macro expands to depends on what argument *x* is passed to it.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Parameterized macros are a useful source-level mechanism for performing in-line expansion, but in languages such as C where they use simple textual substitution, they have a number of severe disadvantages over other mechanisms for performing in-line expansion, such as inline functions.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The parameterized macros used in languages such as Lisp, PL/I and Scheme, on the other hand, are much more powerful, able to make decisions about what code to produce based on their arguments; thus, they can effectively be used to perform run-time code generation.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Languages such as C and some assembly languages have rudimentary macro systems, implemented as preprocessors to the compiler or assembler.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] C preprocessor macros work by simple textual substitution at the token, rather than the character level.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] However, the macro facilities of more sophisticated assemblers, e.g., IBM High Level Assembler (HLASM) can't be implemented with a preprocessor; the code for assembling instructions and data is interspersed with the code for assembling macro invocations.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] A classic use of macros is in the computer typesetting system TeX and its derivatives, where most functionality is based on macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] MacroML is an experimental system that seeks to reconcile static typing and macro systems.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Nemerle has typed syntax macros, and one productive way to think of these syntax macros is as a multi-stage computation.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Some major applications have been written as text macro invoked by other applications, e.g., by XEDIT in CMS.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Some languages, such as PHP, can be embedded in free-format text, or the source code of other languages.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The mechanism by which the code fragments are recognised (for instance, being bracketed by `<?php` and `?>`) is similar to a textual macro language, but they are much more powerful, fully featured languages.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros in the PL/I language are written in a subset of PL/I itself: the compiler executes "preprocessor statements" at compilation time, and the output of this execution forms part of the code that is compiled.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The ability to use a familiar procedural language as the macro language gives power much greater than that of text substitution macros, at the expense of a larger and slower compiler.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros in PL/I, as well as in many assemblers, may have side effects, e.g., setting variables that other macros can access.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Frame technology's frame macros have their own command syntax but can also contain text in any language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Each frame is both a generic component in a hierarchy of nested subassemblies, and a procedure for integrating itself with its subassembly frames (a recursive process that resolves integration conflicts in favor of higher level subassemblies).
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The outputs are custom documents, typically compilable source modules.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Frame technology can avoid the proliferation of similar but subtly different components, an issue that has plagued software development since the invention of macros and subroutines.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Most assembly languages have less powerful procedural macro facilities, for example allowing a block of code to be repeated N times for loop unrolling; but these have a completely different syntax from the actual assembly language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macro systems—such as the C preprocessor described earlier—that work at the level of lexical tokens cannot preserve the lexical structure reliably.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Syntactic macro systems work instead at the level of abstract syntax trees, and preserve the lexical structure of the original program.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The most widely used implementations of syntactic macro systems are found in Lisp-like languages.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] These languages are especially suited for this style of macro due to their uniform, parenthesized syntax (known as S-expressions).
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In particular, uniform syntax makes it easier to determine the invocations of macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Lisp macros transform the program structure itself, with the full language available to express such transformations.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] While syntactic macros are often found in Lisp-like languages, they are also available in other languages such as Prolog, Erlang, Dylan, Scala, Nemerle, Rust, Elixir, Nim, Haxe, and Julia.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] They are also available as third-party extensions to JavaScript and C#.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Before Lisp had macros, it had so-called FEXPRs, function-like operators whose inputs were not the values computed by the arguments but rather the syntactic forms of the arguments, and whose output were values to be used in the computation.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In other words, FEXPRs were implemented at the same level as EVAL, and provided a window into the meta-evaluation layer.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This was generally found to be a difficult model to reason about effectively.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In 1963, Timothy Hart proposed adding macros to Lisp 1.5 in AI Memo 57: MACRO Definitions for LISP.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] An anaphoric macro is a type of programming macro that deliberately captures some form supplied to the macro which may be referred to by an anaphor (an expression referring to another).
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Anaphoric macros first appeared in Paul Graham's On Lisp and their name is a reference to linguistic anaphora—the use of words as a substitute for preceding words.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Hygienic macros have been standardized for Scheme in the R5RS, R6RS, and R7RS standards.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] A number of competing implementations of hygienic macros exist such as `syntax-rules`, `syntax-case`, explicit renaming, and syntactic closures.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Both `syntax-rules` and `syntax-case` have been standardized in the Scheme standards.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Recently, Racket has combined the notions of hygienic macros with a "tower of evaluators", so that the syntactic expansion time of one macro system is the ordinary runtime of another block of code, and showed how to apply interleaved expansion and parsing in a non-parenthesized language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] A number of languages other than Scheme either implement hygienic macros or implement partially hygienic systems.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Examples include Scala, Rust, Elixir, Julia, Dylan, Nim, and Nemerle.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] ) enables the creation of new syntactic constructs (e.g.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] ) indistinguishable from those built into the language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] , it is possible to define the latter in terms of the former using macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] and hygienic macros, which enables a programmer to design their own control abstractions, such as looping and early exit constructs, without the need to build them into the language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] can be implemented in a way that is both natural and efficient.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros can also be used to introduce new binding constructs.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] into the application of a function to a set of arguments.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Felleisen conjectures that these three categories make up the primary legitimate uses of macros in such a system.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Others have proposed alternative uses of macros, such as anaphoric macros in macro systems that are unhygienic or allow selective unhygienic transformation.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The interaction of macros and other language features has been a productive area of research.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] For example, components and modules are useful for large-scale programming, but the interaction of macros and these other constructs must be defined for their use together.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Module and component-systems that can interact with macros have been proposed for Scheme and other languages with macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] For example, the Racket language extends the notion of a macro system to a syntactic tower, where macros can be written in languages including macros, using hygiene to ensure that syntactic layers are distinct and allowing modules to export macros to other modules.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros are normally used to map a short string (macro invocation) to a longer sequence of instructions.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Another, less common, use of macros is to do the reverse: to map a sequence of instructions to a macro string.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This was the approach taken by the STAGE2 Mobile Programming System, which used a rudimentary macro compiler (called SIMCMP) to map the specific instruction set of a given computer into *machine-independent* macros.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Applications (notably compilers) written in these machine-independent macros can then be run without change on any computer equipped with the rudimentary macro compiler.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The first application run in such a context is a more sophisticated and powerful macro compiler, written in the machine-independent macro language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This macro compiler is applied to itself, in a bootstrap fashion, to produce a compiled and much more efficient version of itself.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The advantage of this approach is that complex applications can be ported from one computer to a very different computer with very little effort (for each target machine architecture, just the writing of the rudimentary macro compiler).
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The advent of modern programming languages, notably C, for which compilers are available on virtually all computers, has rendered such an approach superfluous.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This was, however, one of the first instances (if not the first) of compiler bootstrapping.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] A macro instruction embedded in the otherwise assembly source code would be processed by a macro compiler, a preprocessor to the assembler, to replace the macro with one or more assembly instructions.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The resulting code, pure assembly, would be translated to machine code by the assembler.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Two of the earliest programming installations to develop macro languages for the IBM 705 computer were at Dow Chemical Corp. in Delaware and the Air Material Command, Ballistics Missile Logistics Office in California.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Some consider macro instructions as an intermediate step between assembly language programming and the high-level programming languages that followed, such as FORTRAN and COBOL.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] By the late 1950s the macro language was followed by the Macro Assemblers.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] This was a combination of both where one program served both functions, that of a macro pre-processor and an assembler in the same package.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Early examples are FORTRAN Assembly Program (FAP) and Macro Assembly Program (IBMAP) on the IBM 709, 7094, 7040 and 7044, and Autocoder on the 7070/7072/7074.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Eastwood and Douglas McIlroy of Bell Labs introduced conditional and recursive macros into the popular SAP assembler, creating what is known as Macro SAP.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] McIlroy's 1960 paper was seminal in the area of extending any (including high-level) programming languages through macro processors.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macro Assemblers allowed assembly language programmers to implement their own macro-language and allowed limited portability of code between two machines running the same CPU but different operating systems, for example, early versions of MS-DOS and CP/M-86.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] The macro library would need to be written for each target machine but not the overall assembly language program.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Note that more powerful macro assemblers allowed use of conditional assembly constructs in macro instructions that could generate different code on different machines or different operating systems, reducing the need for multiple libraries.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In the 1980s and early 1990s, desktop PCs were only running at a few MHz and assembly language routines were commonly used to speed up programs written in C, Fortran, Pascal and others.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] These languages, at the time, used different calling conventions.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Macros could be used to interface routines written in assembly language to the front end of applications written in almost any language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Again, the basic assembly language code remained the same, only the macro libraries needed to be written for each target language.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] In modern operating systems such as Unix and its derivatives, operating system access is provided through subroutines, usually provided by dynamic libraries.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] High-level languages such as C offer comprehensive access to operating system functions, obviating the need for assembler language programs for such functionality.
[src:janet-language/macro-computer-science] Moreover, standard libraries of several newer programming languages, such as Go, actively discourage the use of syscalls in favor of platform-agnostic libraries as well if not necessary, to improve portability and security.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] In computer programming, an **S-expression** (or **symbolic expression**, abbreviated as **sexpr** or **sexp**) is an expression in a like-named notation for nested list (tree-structured) data.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] S-expressions were invented for, and popularized by, the programming language Lisp, which uses them for source code as well as data.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] *y*) where *x* and *y* are S-expressions.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] This definition reflects LISP's representation of a list as a series of "cells", each one an ordered pair.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] In plain lists, *y* points to the next cell (if any), thus forming a list.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The recursive clause of the definition means that both this representation and the S-expression notation can represent any binary tree.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] `NIL` is the special end-of-list object (alternatively written `()`, which is the only representation in Scheme).
[src:janet-language/s-expression] In the Lisp family of programming languages, S-expressions are used to represent both source code and data.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Other uses of S-expressions are in Lisp-derived languages such as DSSSL, and as mark-up in communication protocols like IMAP and John McCarthy's CBCL.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] It is also used as text representation of WebAssembly.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The details of the syntax and supported data types vary in the different languages, but the most common feature among these languages is the use of S-expressions and prefix notation.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] There are many variants of the S-expression format, supporting a variety of different syntaxes for different datatypes.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The character `#` is often used to prefix extensions to the syntax, e.g.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] `#x10` for hexadecimal integers, or `#\C` for characters.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] When representing source code in Lisp, the first element of an S-expression is commonly an operator or function name and any remaining elements are treated as arguments.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] This is called "prefix notation" or "Polish notation".
[src:janet-language/s-expression] As an example, the Boolean expression written `4 == (2 + 2)` in C, is represented as `(= 4 (+ 2 2))` in Lisp's s-expr-based prefix notation.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] As noted above, the precise definition of "atom" varies across LISP-like languages.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] A quoted string can typically contain anything but a quote, while an unquoted identifier atom can typically contain anything but quotes, whitespace characters, parentheses, brackets, braces, backslashes, and semicolons.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] In either case, a prohibited character can typically be included by escaping it with a preceding backslash.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The recursive case of the definition of S-expressions is traditionally implemented using cons cells.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] S-expressions were originally intended only for data to be manipulated by M-expressions, but the first implementation of Lisp was an interpreter of S-expression encodings of M-expressions, and Lisp programmers soon became accustomed to using S-expressions for both code and data.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] This means that Lisp is homoiconic; that is, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Nested lists can be written as S-expressions: `((milk juice) (honey marmalade))` is a two-element S-expression whose elements are also two-element S-expressions.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The whitespace-separated notation used in Lisp (and this article) is typical.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Line breaks (newline characters) usually qualify as separators.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Program code can be written in S-expressions, usually using prefix notation.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] S-expressions can be read in Lisp using the function READ.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] READ reads the textual representation of an S-expression and returns Lisp data.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The function PRINT can be used to output an S-expression.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The output then can be read with the function READ, when all printed data objects have a readable representation.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Lisp has readable representations for numbers, strings, symbols, lists and many other data types.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Program code can be formatted as pretty printed S-expressions using the function PPRINT (note: with two Ps, short for *pretty*-print).
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Lisp programs are valid S-expressions, but not all S-expressions are valid Lisp programs.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] `(1.0 + 3.1)` is a valid S-expression, but not a valid Lisp program, since Lisp uses prefix notation and a floating point number (here 1.0) is not valid as an operation (the first element of the expression).
[src:janet-language/s-expression] An S-expression preceded by a single quotation mark, as in `'x`, is syntactic sugar for a quoted S-expression, in this case `(quote x)`.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] S-expressions are also used for WebAssembly text format.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] S-expressions are often compared to XML: one key difference is that S-expressions have just one form of containment, the dotted pair, while XML tags can contain simple attributes, other tags, or CDATA, each using different syntax.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Another is that S-expressions do not define a reference mechanism, whereas XML provides a notion of unique identifiers and references to them.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] For simple use cases, S-expressions are simpler than XML, but for more advanced use cases, XML has a query language called XPath which many tools and third party libraries use to simplify the handling of XML data.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Standards for some Lisp-derived programming languages include a specification for their S-expression syntax.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] These include Common Lisp (ANSI standard document ANSI INCITS 226-1994 (R2004)), Scheme (R5RS and R6RS), and ISLISP.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] In May 1997, Ron Rivest submitted an Internet Draft to be considered for publication as an RFC.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The draft defined a syntax based on Lisp S-expressions but intended for general-purpose data storage and exchange (similar to XML) rather than specifically for programming.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] It was never approved as an RFC, but it has since been cited and used by other RFCs (e.g.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] RFC 2693) and several other publications.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] It was originally intended for use in SPKI.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Rivest's format defines an S-expression as being either an octet-string (a series of bytes) or a finite list of other S-expressions.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] It describes three interchange formats for expressing this structure.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] One is the "advanced transport", which is very flexible in terms of formatting, and is syntactically similar to Lisp-style expressions, but they are not identical.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] The advanced transport, for example, allows octet-strings to be represented verbatim (the string's length followed by a colon and the entire raw string), a quoted form allowing escape characters, hexadecimal, Base64, or placed directly as a "token" if it meets certain conditions.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Rivest's draft defines a canonical representation "for digital signature purposes".
[src:janet-language/s-expression] It is intended to be compact, easier to parse, and unique for any abstract S-expression.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] It only allows verbatim strings, and prohibits whitespace as formatting outside strings.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] This format has not been widely adapted for use outside of SPKI (some of the users being GnuPG, libgcrypt, Nettle, and GNU lsh).
[src:janet-language/s-expression] Rivest's S-expressions web page provides C source code for a parser and generator (available under the MIT license), which could be adapted and embedded into other programs.
[src:janet-language/s-expression] In addition, there are no restrictions on independently implementing the format.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:janet-language/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
